{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20846"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20846"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13721"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12355"},{"type":"tags","id":"12671"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33035"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism by which tumor cells can express antigens that stimulate an immune response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selective hypermethylation of tumor suppressor gene promoters","Upregulation of immune checkpoint inhibitory ligands","Expression of alternatively spliced isoforms of normal proteins","Secretion of immunosuppressive cytokines into the tumor microenvironment","Production of variant proteins from mutated genes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of variant proteins from mutated genes\u003C/strong\u003E. Malignant tumors frequently harbor both driver mutations (which contribute to the cancer phenotype) and passenger mutations (which do not affect cancer cell fitness). These mutations can result in altered proteins that the immune system recognizes as foreign because they have never been encountered before. The mutational load in tumors correlates with the strength of the host CD8+ cytotoxic T-cell response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective hypermethylation of tumor suppressor gene promoters\u003C/strong\u003E - This epigenetic mechanism typically silences genes that would normally prevent cancer development. It generally reduces protein expression rather than creating novel antigens, and thus would not typically stimulate immune responses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpregulation of immune checkpoint inhibitory ligands\u003C/strong\u003E - This is actually a mechanism by which tumors evade immune destruction. Molecules like PD-L1 interact with immune checkpoint receptors on T cells to suppress their activity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpression of alternatively spliced isoforms of normal proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While alternative splicing can generate protein variants, these are usually recognized as self by the immune system since they are part of normal protein processing and are subject to central tolerance mechanisms.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of immunosuppressive cytokines into the tumor microenvironment\u003C/strong\u003E - This is another immune evasion strategy used by tumors to inhibit immune cell function, not a mechanism that stimulates immune responses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanisms by which tumors can express antigens include overexpression of normal cellular proteins (like tyrosinase in melanomas), aberrant expression of proteins normally silenced in adult tissues (such as cancer-testis antigens like MAGE), and expression of viral proteins in virus-associated cancers (such as those caused by Epstein-Barr virus or human papillomavirus).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignant tumors express various molecules that can be recognized by the immune system as foreign antigens.","Neoantigens produced from genes with driver and passenger mutations are important tumor antigens that can elicit immune responses.","Tumor antigens can also include overexpressed normal proteins, aberrantly expressed proteins, and viral proteins in virus-associated cancers."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 309-311."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20846"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:36:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T11:37:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13721"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name